{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506959"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:48:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:48:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2593"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2593"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.02,0.56,0.33,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2593"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106685"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2593"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2593"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89165"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"393"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2771"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38597"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42526"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44783"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106685"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about a pigmented lesion on her back that she first noticed three months ago. She believes it has increased in size during this time. The lesion is not itchy, bleeding, or painful. She has no personal history of skin lesions or skin cancer, and no known family history of skin cancer. She reports significant sun exposure and multiple sunburns during childhood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has Fitzpatrick type 2 skin. On her posterior right scapula, there is an asymmetrical lesion measuring 3 x 3 cm with irregular borders. The lesion contains three different shades of brown and black. There are no surrounding skin changes or palpable lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Punch biopsy","Deep shave biopsy","Excisional biopsy with a 2mm margin","Excisional biopsy with a 2cm margin","Sentinel lymph node biopsy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a suspicious pigmented lesion demonstrating multiple concerning features according to the ABCDE criteria (Asymmetry, Border irregularity, Colour variation, Diameter \u0026gt;6mm, and Evolution). Additional risk factors include fair skin type and childhood sun exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcisional biopsy with a 2mm margin\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard initial management for suspicious pigmented lesions. This approach allows complete histological assessment and accurate Breslow thickness measurement if melanoma is confirmed. The narrow margin minimises tissue disruption while ensuring complete lesion removal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPunch biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated for suspicious pigmented lesions as it samples only a portion of the lesion. This partial sampling can miss areas of deeper invasion or ulceration, leading to understaging. Additionally, punch biopsy can disrupt lymphatic drainage patterns, potentially compromising future sentinel lymph node biopsy if required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeep shave biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as it may transect the base of the lesion, making accurate Breslow thickness measurement impossible. This can lead to understaging and inappropriate management decisions. Furthermore, like punch biopsy, it can disrupt lymphatic drainage patterns and compromise future staging procedures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcisional biopsy with a 2cm margin\u003C/strong\u003E is excessive for initial diagnostic biopsy and may complicate future management. Wide local excision margins are determined after melanoma is confirmed and staged, based on Breslow thickness. Performing an unnecessarily wide excision initially can complicate lymphatic mapping if sentinel node biopsy is later required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESentinel lymph node biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is only considered after melanoma diagnosis is confirmed histologically. The decision to perform SLNB is based on factors including Breslow thickness, presence of ulceration, and mitotic rate. It would be inappropriate to perform this procedure before confirming the diagnosis and determining these prognostic factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Suspicious pigmented lesions require complete excisional biopsy with 2mm margins for accurate histological assessment and Breslow scoring.","Punch biopsy and deep shave biopsy are contraindicated for suspicious pigmented lesions as they may compromise accurate staging.","Wide local excision margins are determined by Breslow thickness after melanoma is confirmed histologically."],"references":["Johns M, O\u0027Bryen J, Banney L, Neale R. Skin cancer prevention in Australia. Aust J Gen Pract. 2024;53(8):524-528. doi:10.31128/AJGP-11-23-7010. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39099113/","Adybeik D, Ciranni D, Moayed Alaei L, 2019. Punch Biopsy is best avoided for clinically suspicious pigmented lesions. Vol 48, Issue 6, June 2019. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-02-19-4837 Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/june/punch-biopsy-is-best-avoided-for-clinically-suspic","Thompson J, Scolyer R,  Kefford R, 2012. Melanoma. Australian Journal for General Practitioners Vol 41 pp.470-473. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/july/melanoma-guide","Chan J, Wood B,  Harvey N, 2017. Skin biopsy in the diagnosis of neoplastic skin disease. Australian Journal for General Practitioners 2017 Vol. 46 Pages 289-294 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28472574/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89165"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2593"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89165"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-21T20:16:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-21T20:16:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2593"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106685"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag